						               													<description>&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#136;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#170;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#131;&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#175;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#187;&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#170;&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#162;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#187;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#136;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#170;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#188;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#136; (Trick or Treat) is a card game from Japan. It uses a rock-paper-scissors mechanism to collect chocolate or sweets whilst going Trick Or Treat.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Players have three cards in hand, Trick, Candy, Chocolate, and choose one to place face-down. When all players have chosen, the cards are turned up and resolved.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;If a majority have chosen candy or chocolate, then cards are collected from the sweets deck. But if a trick card is in play, that player can take cards from the others. The different majorities are resolved in different ways.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;There is a deck of sweets shuffled and placed face-down. Depending on who won the round, cards are turned face-up and collected from the deck. these cards include candy, chocolate and ghosts. Players are trying to collect sets of candy or chocolate to win.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;If a ghost turns up, it is set aside but the payer gets to steal cards from their neighbour.&amp;#10;user summary&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
